INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("27", "1", "2016-12-21 23:14:16", "2016-12-22 04:14:16", "<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-368\" src=\"https://thecoffeebean813.github.io/i2.wp.com/coffeebean506.files.wordpress.com/2016/11/coffeecherriesmaina53e.jpg?resize=556%2C314&amp;ssl=1\" sizes=\"(max-width: 556px) 100vw, 556px\" alt=\"coffeecherriesmain\" width=\"556\" height=\"314\" />\r\n\r\nBlueberries, Pomegranates, Oranges. Pineapples. All easy-to-buy fruits we know are good for us. But what if we told you one of nature’s healthiest foods was something farmers typically used for compost—or even completely threw away as trash?\r\n\r\nCoffee is one healthy vice; Along with keeping you from drooling all over your desk mid-day, it’s low in calories, packed with antioxidants and may protect against ailments like Type II diabetes, Parkinson’s and Liver disease. However, the thin and juicy coating on the outside of the coffee bean does this and more. A true superfood packed with antioxidants—due to the uber-concentrated polyphenols—coffee fruit has the power to boost the immune system, protect against free radicals and act as an anti-inflammatory.", "Natures Superfood: Coffee Cherries", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "natures-superfood-coffee-cherries", "", "", "2016-12-21 23:14:16", "2016-12-22 04:14:16", "", "0", "http://localhost/?p=27", "0", "post", "", "0");
